{"cursor":"8184","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":":In politics, the term Incrementalism is also used as a synonym for\n[[Gradualism#Politics and society|Gradualism]].\n\n\n'Incrementalism' is a method of working by adding to a project using many small\n(often unplanned), incremental changes instead of a few (extensively planned)\nlarge jumps. Wikipedia, for example, illustrates the concept by building an\nencyclopedia bit by bit, continually adding to it. In a similar vein, according\nto legend Virgil wrote the Aeneid in an incremental process, averaging three\nlines per day, http://wiki.answers.com/Q/How_many_pages_of_the_Aeneid_did_V-\nirgil_write_per_day and the Georgics even more slowly at an average of one\nline per day. http://links.jstor.org/sici?sici=0009-\n840X(189807)1%3A12%3A6%3C306%3AHROCVV%3E2.0.CO%3B2-2 Logical\nincrementalism implies that the steps in the process are sensible. Quinn,\nJ.B., 1978. Strategic change: logical incrementalism. Sloan Management Review 20\n(1), 7â21. Logical Incrementalism focuses on \"the Power-Behavioral\nApproach to planning rather than to the Formal Systems Planning Approach.\" \nQuin, J. B. (1978). Strategic Change: \"Logical Incrementalism.\" Sloan Management\nReview, 20 (1), p7.  In public policy, incrementalism refers to the method\nof change by which many small policy changes are enacted over time in order to\ncreate a larger broad based policy change. This was the theoretical policy of\nrationality developed by Lindblom to be seen as a middle way between the\nrational actor model and bounded rationality, as both long term goal driven\npolicy rationality and satisficing were not seen as adequate.\n","linknr":168,"url":"Incrementalism","recorded":1374764469,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Incrementalism&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Incrementalism&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licen